                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d434">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">838.51/1374: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The High Commissioner in Haiti</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Russell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Port au Prince</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-09-15T12:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 15, 1922—noon</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>[Received September 16—10:05 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>106. In reply to my note containing the suggestions made by the Department’s 73,
                    September 9, 4 p.m. the Haitian Government informs me that it has taken note of
                    suggestions and will place them before the legislative committee now examining
                    the proposed law.<note n="62" xml:id="d434fn62">The law, embodying the
                        Department’s suggestions, was passed by the Council of State Sept. 27,
                        approved by President Borno Oct. 2, and published in <hi rend="italic">Le
                            Moniteur</hi> Oct. 5, 1922.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Russell</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
